\section{Introduction}
Image classification is a core computer vision problem where a model predicts the category of an input image. Deep learning, especially Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), has become a standard approach because CNNs can automatically learn hierarchical visual features directly from raw pixel data.

This project addresses multi-class image classification on the CIFAR-10 dataset. CIFAR-10 contains 60{,}000 color images of size $32\times32$, grouped into 10 classes: airplane, automobile, bird, cat, deer, dog, frog, horse, ship, and truck. The dataset is split into 50{,}000 training images and 10{,}000 test images.

The objective of this work is to design, train, and evaluate a CNN that demonstrates core deep learning principles in architecture design, optimization strategy, model regularization, and performance interpretation.

\section{Methodology}
\subsection{Data Preparation}
The dataset was loaded using the Keras CIFAR-10 API \texttt{keras.datasets.cifar10.load\_data()}.

Pixel values were normalized from the integer range $[0, 255]$ to floating-point range $[0, 1]$. The original 50{,}000 training samples were further split into:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Training set: 40{,}000 images
    \item Validation set: 10{,}000 images
    \item Test set: 10{,}000 images (official CIFAR-10 test split)
\end{itemize}

Data augmentation was applied during training to improve generalization:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Zero-padding followed by random cropping back to $32\times32$
    \item Random horizontal flipping
    \item Small random rotation
\end{itemize}
These transformations increase variability in training samples without changing class labels, helping reduce overfitting.

\subsection{CNN Architecture}
The model is a deep CNN with three convolutional blocks followed by a classification head. Key components include:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Convolutional layers for feature extraction
    \item ReLU activation functions for non-linearity
    \item Batch normalization for training stability
    \item Max pooling for spatial downsampling
    \item Dropout for regularization
    \item Global average pooling before output
    \item Softmax output layer for 10-class probability prediction
\end{itemize}
\begin{figure}[!htbp]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.82\textwidth]{cifar10_cnn_architecture.png}
    \caption{CNN architecture used for CIFAR-10 classification.}
    \label{fig:cnn_architecture}
\end{figure}
This design was chosen to balance representational capacity and regularization for small images, while maintaining computational efficiency.

\subsection{Training Procedure and Hyperparameters}
The model was implemented in TensorFlow/Keras and trained with:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Optimizer: AdamW (fallback to Adam if AdamW unavailable)
    \item Initial learning rate: $1\times10^{-3}$
    \item Weight decay: $1\times10^{-4}$
    \item Batch size: 128
    \item Maximum epochs: 80
    \item Loss function: Sparse Categorical Cross-Entropy
\end{itemize}

Training strategies:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Early stopping}: monitored validation loss and restored best weights
    \item \textbf{Learning-rate scheduling}: ReduceLROnPlateau reduced LR when validation loss plateaued
    \item \textbf{Weight decay and dropout}: limited overfitting
    \item \textbf{Data augmentation}: improved robustness
\end{itemize}

