\section{Discussion}
The model achieved strong performance on CIFAR-10 for a custom CNN. Training and validation curves indicate learning progress, while the gap between them provides evidence about generalization behavior. With regularization (dropout, weight decay, augmentation) and early stopping, overfitting was controlled.

Class-wise analysis from the confusion matrix indicates that visually similar categories were more likely to be confused (for example, cat vs dog, deer vs horse, and automobile vs truck). This is expected because CIFAR-10 images are small and sometimes contain ambiguous viewpoints or backgrounds.

Potential improvements include:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Stronger architectures (e.g., ResNet variants)
    \item Advanced augmentation (mixup, cutout, RandAugment)
    \item Hyperparameter search (learning rate, dropout schedule, optimizer settings)
    \item Test-time augmentation and ensembling
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion}
This project implemented an end-to-end deep learning pipeline for CIFAR-10 image classification using TensorFlow/Keras. The work covered dataset preparation, CNN design, model training with modern regularization strategies, and quantitative and qualitative evaluation.

The final model demonstrates that a carefully regularized CNN can provide good classification performance on CIFAR-10 while remaining interpretable and computationally practical. The results and analysis also highlight common class-confusion patterns and suggest clear directions for future improvement.

